# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1887-cleveland-blues-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1887 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 17th season of the franchise.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-brooklyn-grays-season] The **1887 Brooklyn Grays** finished the season in sixth place.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1887 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 16th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 12th in the National League and the third at the first West Side Park.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished third in the National League with a record of 71–50.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1887 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished in second place in the American Association with a record of 81–45, 14 games behind the St.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Following a horrible 1886 season, in which the Red Stockings finished under .500 for the first time in team history, the team hired Gus Schmelz to become the new manager.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons of the National League in 1886 to a 43–79 record.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] He also managed the Columbus Buckeyes of the American Association in 1883, leading them to a 69–39 record and a second-place finish.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati signed George Tebeau to his first professional contract, and acquired Hugh Nicol from the St.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns in a trade with sent Jack Boyle and $350 to the Browns.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol hit .206 with 19 RBI and 38 stolen bases, as well as scoring 44 runs in 67 games in 1886.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly had a great season, as he hit .306 with a team high ten home runs and had 96 RBI, as well as 50 stolen bases.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill led the club with a .311 batting average, and his 97 RBI tied him with Frank Fennelly for the team high.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol led the American Association with 138 stolen bases.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Mike Smith emerged as the ace of the staff, as he had a 34–17 record and a league best 2.94 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Tony Mullane also had a solid season, as he had a 31–17 record with a 3.24 ERA in 48 starts.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got off to a fast start, winning their first five games, however, Cincinnati lost six of their next seven games to fall to 6–6.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a 21–22 record after 43 games, before winning nine of ten to rise up to third place with a 30–23 record.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] After going 3–6 in their next nine games, Cincinnati had a season-high ten-game winning streak.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they remained in third place, 8.5 games behind the St.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings continued to play good baseball for the remainder of the season, as they finished the year in second place with a record of 81–54, fourteen games behind the first-place Browns.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The **1887 Detroit Wolverines season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The team won the 1887 National League pennant, then defeated the St.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The season was the team's seventh since it entered the National League in 1881.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] It was the first World Series championship for the Detroit Wolverines and the City of Detroit.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] On March 13, after training in Macon, Georgia‚ the Wolverines began a six-week exhibition tour through the South and Midwest.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Catching duties were divided between **Charlie Ganzel** (51 games at catcher) and **Charlie Bennett** (45 games at catcher).
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Both were good defensive catchers, though neither hit particularly well.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Bennett had a better fielding percentage than Ganzel (.951 to .913), but Ganzel was stronger in range factor (6.78 to 5.64) and fielding runs (9 to 2).
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Bennett's career in baseball ended when he lost both his legs in a train accident.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] When the Detroit Tigers opened their new ballpark in 1896, they named it Bennett Park in his honor.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] It remained Bennett Park until 1912, when the newly built stadium on the same site was named Navin Field.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] First baseman **Dan Brouthers** was the first of four future Hall of Famers to play for the 1887 Wolverines.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Brouthers won five batting titles and seven slugging titles, and his career batting average of .342 is the 9th highest in major league history.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Brouthers was a key to the Wolverines offensive output in 1887 as he led the National League in runs (153), doubles (36), extra base hits (68), on-base percentage (.426), times on base (246), and OPS (.988).
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was also among the league leaders with a .338 batting average (3rd in the NL), .562 slugging percentage (2nd in the NL), 20 triples, 12 home runs (5th in the NL), 101 RBIs (4th in the NL), 71 walks (4th in the NL), and an at-bat-to-strikeout ratio of 55.6 (2nd in NL).
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The second baseman duties were split between **Fred Dunlap** and **Hardy Richardson**.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Dunlap played 65 games at second base but missed two months due to an injury.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] As a result, Richardson played 64 games at second base in addition to 58 games as the left fielder.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Richardson was a big contributor to the 1887 Wolverines, as he hit for a .327 average with 51 extra base hits, 131 runs scored, 178 hits and 94 RBIs.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Richardson was also a good fielder both at second base and in left field.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Third baseman **Deacon White** was also part of "The Big Four" acquired from Buffalo before the 1886 season, and is the second of four future Hall-of-Famers on the team.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] White won two batting crowns earlier in his career but was 39 years old in 1887.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He still hit for a .303 batting average and had 11 triples, 75 RBIs and 20 stolen bases.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] White was a nonsmoking, Bible-toting, church-going deacon.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] According to Lee Allen in *The National League Story* (1961), White was one of the last people to believe that the earth is flat.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Right fielder **Sam Thompson**, known as "Big Sam," was the third future Hall of Famer on the 1887 Detroit team.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Thompson was in his prime in 1887 and had a tremendous year.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was the National League batting champion with a .372 average, and he also led the league in slugging percentage (.571), hits (203), total bases (311), triples (23), RBIs (166), and runs created (127).
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] His 1887 total of 166 RBIs stood as a major league record for 40 years until Lou Gehrig broke it in 1927.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] 2 on the all-time home run list at the time of his retirement.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Center fielder **Ned Hanlon** was the fourth future Hall of Famer on the 1887 Detroit team.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Though inducted into the Hall of Fame based on his later performance as a manager, Hanlon was a good fielding center fielder who had tremendous speed and range.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1887, he stole 69 bases for the Wolverines.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He also hit .291 with seven stolen bases and 4 RBIs in the 1887 World Series.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The left fielder duties were split between second baseman/outfielder **Hardy Richardson**, and pitcher/outfielder **Larry Twitchell**.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In addition to pitching 15 games for the Wolverines, Twitchell played 44 games in left field and 9 games in center field.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Twitchell had a .333 batting average and collected 51 RBIs in just 264 at bats.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In his 15 games as a pitcher, Twitchell had a record of 11–1.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines' #1 pitcher in 1887 was **Charlie Getzien**.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Getzien had a record of 29–13 for the 1887 team.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Getzien started 42 games, pitched 41 complete games, and had an ERA of 3.73.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was among the league leaders in wins, win percentage (.690), inning pitched (366.2), and strikeouts (135).
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was also first in the league with 24 home runs allowed.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In the 1887 World Series, Getzien had a record of 4–2 with a 2.48 ERA.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Baldwin played four seasons with the Wolverines.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1886, Baldwin had a record of 42–13 (the most wins ever by a Detroit pitcher) with a 2.24 ERA in 487 innings pitched, striking out 323 of 1936 batters faced.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Baldwin also completed 55 of 56 games, seven of which were shutouts.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1887, Baldwin's appearances were reduced from 56 games to 24, and from 487 innings to 211.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He won only 13 games in the regular season for the 1887 Wolverines, but in World Series play, Baldwin pitched 5 complete games for a 4–1 record and a 1.50 ERA.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines' #3 pitcher was **George Edward "Stump" Weidman**.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Weidman led the National League with a 1.80 ERA for Detroit in 1881.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1887, Weidman returned to the Wolverines, where he went 13–7.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] By late July, Weidman fell out of favor with manager William Watkins who considered Weidman to be a malcontent.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines sold Weidman to the New York Metropolitans on August 5, 1887.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines #4 pitcher was **Pete Conway**.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Despite his 8–9 record in 1887, Conway had the lowest ERA (2.90) among the Detroit starters.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The 1887 Wolverines finished the season with a record of 79–45.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] They outscored their opponents by more than 250 runs—969 to 714.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] They also led the National League in team batting average, runs scored and slugging.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Louis Browns in the 1887 World Series, 10 games to 5.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] After the Wolverines won the National League pennant, owner Fred Stearns challenged the American Association champion St.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines and the Browns would play "a series of contests for supremacy" of the baseball world.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] This early "world series" consisted of fifteen games – played in Pittsburgh, Brooklyn, New York, Philadelphia, Boston, Washington, Baltimore and Chicago, as well as Detroit and St.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines claimed their eighth victory – and thus the championship – in the eleventh game.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The **1887 Indianapolis Hoosiers** finished with a 37–89 record in the National League, finishing in last place in their first season in Indianapolis.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] They had played the previous three seasons in St.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Following the 1886 season, the Maroons franchise was purchased by the National League and subsequently sold to John T.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] On March 8, the Hoosiers additionally purchased a number of players who were under league control.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Technically, these players were purchased from the Maroons franchise.
[src:1887-cleveland-blues-season/1887-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Among these players were Henry Boyle, John Cahill, Jerry Denny, Jack Glasscock, Egyptian Healy, John Kirby, Jack McGeachey, George Myers, Otto Schomberg, and Emmett Seery.
